rld and history, and how he uses spatial images throughout the dialogues to critique Athens's tragic overreach in the Peloponnesian War. Far from merely an incidental backdrop in the dialogues, place etches the tragic intersection of the mortal and the immortal, good and evil, and Athens's past, present, and future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aPlace (Philosophy). 4aPhilosophy : Ancient Greek Philosophy. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 4aPhilosophy : Plato. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143846271440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438462714423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438462714/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles